@startuml build-orchestration-subagents
title Persona Build — Sub-agent Assignment (dependency-gated DAG, NOT load-spreading)

' ============================================================================
'  DESIGN INTENT — read before the diagram
'  Sub-agents are assigned by the build's REAL data dependencies, never to
'  "spread load across whatever is idle". Parallelism is OPENED only where the
'  work is provably independent (capabilities do not depend on each other; tool
'  tests do not depend on each other) and CLOSED at barriers where cross-item
'  context is genuinely required (identity, IR assembly, promote).
'
'  There are exactly TWO fan-out points, each falling on a natural independence
'  seam that already exists in the v3 build chronology:
'    behavior_core -> capability_enumeration -> [per-capability resolution] -> agent_ir
'  Fan-out #1 = per-capability resolution.  Fan-out #2 = per-tool test.
'  Everything else is a single serial "lead" session.
'
'  See the legend at the bottom: "Why this is not managed chaos" plus the
'  explicitly REJECTED pool-of-generic-workers model.
' ============================================================================

skinparam maxMessageSize 260
skinparam ConditionEndStyle hline
skinparam shadowing false

start

partition "Serial spine — single lead session (claude-sonnet-4-6, subscription auth)" {
  :behavior_core;
  note right
    Persona identity: motivation / stance / northStar / risk / speed.
    EVERY downstream step depends on it -> cannot parallelize.
    Already streams early via --include-partial-messages (runner.rs:576-628).
  end note

  :capability_enumeration;
  note right
    Produces the fan-out SET = the list of capabilities,
    plus the UNION of the connectors/APIs they reference.
    This is what makes fan-out #1 knowable up front.
  end note

  :resolve SHARED connectors ONCE;
  note right
    The "reasonable engineering" step: research each DISTINCT
    connector/API a single time here, not once per capability.
    Output = a connector-context blob injected into every
    capability sub-agent below -> parallel agents never
    redundantly re-research the same GitHub/Slack/etc.
  end note
}

:assign ONE sub-agent per capability;
note right
  Assignment rule (fan-out #1): exactly one sub-agent per enumerated capability.
  Concurrency budget = min(build_budget, |capabilities|), build_budget ~ 2-3,
  governed by run_budget.rs / rate_limiter.rs / resource_governor.rs.
  Scheduler pattern copied from engine/team_assignment_orchestrator.rs:665-711
  (budget = max_parallel - running; tokio::spawn + catch_unwind isolation).
  Each sub-agent:
    * own CLI session dir + own conversation (NO --continue; the shared
      research context is PASSED IN, not resumed)
    * prompt = behavior_core + enumeration + shared-connector blob
    * resolves: trigger, model_override, tool spec, sample I/O, memory policy
    * tags every BuildEvent with agent_id / lane  (the Events-first prerequisite)
end note

partition "Fan-out #1 — per-capability resolution (BOUNDED parallel)" {
  fork
    :resolve capability A;
  fork again
    :resolve capability B;
  fork again
    :resolve capability C ... N;
  end fork
}

partition "Barrier — back to single lead session" {
  :assemble agent_ir;
  note right
    Needs ALL resolved capabilities at once:
      * dedup tool definitions across capabilities
      * reconcile shared connectors + credentialLinks
      * resolve persona-wide fields
      * detect cross-capability conflicts (clashing triggers, dup tool names)
    This cross-item reconciliation is exactly why the fan-out MUST join here
    (a genuine barrier, not a convenience sync).
  end note
  :checkpoint DraftReady -> build_sessions row;
}

if (mode?) then (interactive)
  :park on user test / refine;
  note right
    The clarifying-question gate state machine is SERIAL by design
    (mpsc park/resume, gates.rs Rule 16/17). Multi-agent build is
    scoped to one_shot; interactive resolution stays single-lead.
  end note
else (one_shot)
  :assign ONE sub-agent per tool/connector test;
  note right
    Fan-out #2: tool tests are independent by construction.
    Deterministic option (scripted-tests direction): SKIP the LLM and call
    engine::api_proxy::execute_api_request / healthcheck::run_healthcheck
    per bound connector -> faster, cheaper, non-flaky.
    Same bounded budget + scheduler as fan-out #1.
  end note

  repeat
    fork
      :test tool 1;
    fork again
      :test tool 2;
    fork again
      :test tool 3 ... M;
    end fork
    :aggregate tool-test report;
  backward:fix-pass — LLM corrects agent_ir\nfor each FAILING capability (bounded parallel per failure);
  repeat while (failing tools remain\nAND attempt < MAX_TEST_RETRIES (3)?) is (retry) not (all green / budget exhausted)
endif

partition "Serial — single lead session" {
  :promote_build_draft;
  :materialize initial_state + run Phase-3b verification gate;
}

stop

legend right
  == Why this is NOT managed chaos ==
  * Sub-agents are typed to a UNIT OF WORK (a capability, a tool test),
    not handed arbitrary slices off a queue "just to keep cores busy".
  * The DAG's edges are REAL data dependencies, so a parallel branch can
    never read another branch's half-finished state.
  * Parallelism degree is small + bounded (2-3), matched to how many
    independent units actually exist — not "as many workers as we can spawn".
  * Shared work (connector research) is de-duplicated ONCE up front.
  ....
  == REJECTED model: pool of generic workers ==
  A pool of N identical CLIs pulling "anything" off a work queue to spread
  load. Rejected because:
    * no dependency gating -> a worker could start capability resolution
      before behavior_core exists, or assemble IR before all capabilities are in;
    * redundant research (every worker re-derives shared connectors);
    * non-deterministic ordering -> irreproducible builds + racey checkpoints;
    * unbounded fan-out fights the subscription rate limiter.
  The DAG above gets the SAME parallel speed-up on the genuinely-independent
  parts, without any of these failure modes.
endlegend

@enduml
